In R, there are many quite a few diagnostic tools for MLM, although they are not necessarily straightforward to use. In this note I will show some basic tools.

Running MLM

Importing Data Into R

Well import the data in .sav format.

library(tidyverse)
theme_set(theme_bw())  # Use a different theme for plotting with ggplot2
library(lme4)
library(haven)
# Read in the data (pay attention to the directory)
hsball <- read_sav("../data/hsball.sav")
hsball <- as.data.frame(hsball)  # need this to get the influence statistics

Fitting the model

We will use the example of a cross-level interaction model

crlv_int <- lmer(mathach ~ meanses + sector * ses + (ses | id), 
                 data = hsball)

Diagnostic Plots

1. Residuals (Lv 1.) vs.Fitted Values

For: linearity, specification, outliers, homoscedasticity

You want to see a random blob with no clear patterns, such as a curvillinear shape

# Augment the data with the fitted values and the standardized residuals
resid_df <- mutate(hsball, 
                   .std_resid = resid(crlv_int, scaled = TRUE), 
                   .fitted = fitted(crlv_int))
ggplot(resid_df, 
       aes(x = .fitted, y = .std_resid)) + 
  geom_point() +  # show the points
  geom_smooth()  # add a smoother

The plot shows no clear patterns and there does not appear to be outliers. The residual variance also seems preety constant across different levels of the fitted values. *One thing to note, however, is that the residuals appear to be bounded, which can indicate a ceiling and/or a floor effect. This certainly is due to our outcome variable being bounded with a maximum of 25.

2. Residuals (Lv 1.) vs.Each Predictor

For: linearity, specification, outliers, homoscedasticity

You want to see a random blob with no clear patterns, such as a curvillinear shape

a. For ses

p1 <- ggplot(resid_df, 
       aes(x = ses, y = .std_resid)) + 
  geom_point() +  # show the points
  geom_smooth()  # add a smoother

b. For meanses

p2 <- ggplot(resid_df, 
       aes(x = meanses, y = .std_resid)) + 
  geom_point() +  # show the points
  geom_smooth()  # add a smoother

c. For sector

For categorical predictors, you want to see that the variance and distribution is similar across different levels of the predictor.

p3 <- ggplot(resid_df, 
       aes(x = factor(sector),  # factor() is used for categorical predictor
           y = .std_resid)) + 
  # use `geom_violin()` with categorical predictor
  geom_violin()
gridExtra::grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, nrow = 2L)

The plots did not suggest any major issues with the linearity or homogeneity.

Q-Q Plot for Lv-1 Residuals

For: normality

You want to see the points line up nicely along the 45 degree line

library(lattice)  # need this package to use the built-in functions
qqmath(crlv_int)  # just use the `qqmath()` function on the fitted model

There are some deviations from normality on the two tail areas, which is likely due to less kurtosis because of the boundedness of the outcome variable. Generally the impact of kurtosis is not as severe as skewness, and the above plot did not suggest a major issue to the results.

Q-Q Plot for Lv-2 Residuals

For: normality

At level 2 there can be more then one set of residuals. For example, in this model, we have one set for the random intercept, and the other set for the random slope

# the code is a bit more complex in order to add, but you only need to replace
# the reference lines `crlv_int` with the name of your own model to get the
# plots for your own analyses
qqmath(ranef(crlv_int), 
       panel = function(x) {  
         panel.qqmath(x)
         panel.qqmathline(x)
       })
$id

Normality does not appear to be an issue at level 2.

Variance Inflation Factor (VIF)

For: multicollinearity

library(car)
Loading required package: carData

Attaching package: car

The following object is masked from package:dplyr:

    recode

The following object is masked from package:purrr:

    some
car::vif(crlv_int)
   meanses     sector        ses sector:ses 
  1.240397   1.143776   1.890820   1.792714

As a rule of thumb, one would worry about multicollinearity in the predictors when VIF > 4, and VIF > 10 indicates strong multicollinearity.

Influence Index Plot

For: leverage and outliers

To examine whether some cases gives disproportionately strong influence on the results, we can look at influence index plot and dfbeta

inf_crlv_int <- influence(crlv_int, "id")  # get influence statistics
singular fit
singular fit
car::infIndexPlot(inf_crlv_int)

If you need some cutoffs, the cutoff for dfbeta is \(2 / sqrt{n}\), which would be 0.1581139 in our example; cutoff for Cooks distance is \(4 / (n - 2)\), which would be 0.0253165 in our example.
